Name: Software Dev Hacker Hoodie
Description:
Stay toasty in your server dungeon—or your home office—without sacrificing geek cred. The Software Dev Hacker Hoodie is the ultimate fusion of comfort, functionality, and hacker swagger.

\n \n
    \n
  • \n

    Thermo‑Optimized Lining
    Crafted with a proprietary “404°F Not Found” thermal fabric, this hoodie traps heat where you need it most—so your fingers stay nimble for late‑night commits and emergency bug fixes.

    \n
    • \n
  • \n

    Secret Snack Pocket™
    Tired of that mid-pull‑request growl? Stash your emergency energy gels, granola bars, or the occasional gummy bear in an extra‑deep kangaroo pocket (no one will suspect!).

    \n
    • \n
  • \n

    Cable‑Friendly Design
    Reinforced headphone loops on the hood keep your earbuds from tangling with your mechanical keyboard’s coiled USB cable. Bonus: a hidden pass‑through port lets your phone charge inside your pocket—caffeine for your code, and power for your devices.

    \n
    • \n
  • \n

    Stealth Mode Aesthetic
    Matte‑black, minimalist embroidery of cryptic binary patterns on the chest and sleeves means only fellow devs will notice. No gaudy logos—just pure, unadulterated hacker elegance.

    \n
    • \n
  • \n

    Bug‑Repellent™ Fabric
    We can’t guarantee your code will be bug‑free, but this hoodie’s water‑ and spaghetti‑sauce‑resistant shell keeps real‑world messes at bay.

    \n
    • \n
\n

Whether you’re wrangling a stubborn CI pipeline at 2 AM or pairing‑programming in a frigid conference room, the Software Dev Hacker Hoodie has your back (and your core temperature). Slip it on, drop into stealth mode, and let the world know: you debug in comfort.

\n

Note: Doesn’t grant actual hacking powers—please don’t try to spill coffee on your keyboard to “short‑circuit” your way to admin access.

Name: TypeScript Handbook
Description:
Over 20 years after its introduction to the programming community, JavaScript is now one of the most widespread cross-platform languages ever created. Starting as a small scripting language for adding trivial interactivity to webpages, JavaScript has grown to be a language of choice for both frontend and backend applications of every size. While the size, scope, and complexity of programs written in JavaScript has grown exponentially, the ability of the JavaScript language to express the relationships between different units of code has not. Combined with JavaScript’s rather peculiar runtime semantics, this mismatch between language and program complexity has made JavaScript development a difficult task to manage at scale.
\n
\nThe most common kinds of errors that programmers write can be described as type errors: a certain kind of value was used where a different kind of value was expected. This could be due to simple typos, a failure to understand the API surface of a library, incorrect assumptions about runtime behavior, or other errors. The goal of TypeScript is to be a static typechecker for JavaScript programs - in other words, a tool that runs before your code runs (static) and ensures that the types of the program are correct (typechecked).
